pr_title: add scoping methods to course creator
pr_body:
Partially resolves #4658 

This adds a new segment to the course creation modal which allows users to track a specific set of articles more easily by configuring the 4 scoping methods - PetScan, PagePile, Templates and Categories - in the course creation modal itself.

This is how it looks in action 

https://github.com/WikiEducationFoundation/WikiEduDashboard/assets/10794178/351bbdd7-f3cf-47e2-ace0-84042675fa40
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 1230166618, 'comment_body': '"For an Article Scoped Program, the Dashboard will only track edits to the articles that you have configured it for. After your page has been created, you can add individual articles to track assigning articles to individual editors or by adding them as Available Articles. For larger sets of articles, you can use any of these tools to define articles you want to track."', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 14, 21, 1, 26, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ragesoss', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1230168817, 'comment_body': '"The Category feature on a wiki is used to collect related articles. You can use the name of the Category to tell the Dashboard to track all the articles in that Category."', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 14, 21, 3, 50, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ragesoss', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1230171642, 'comment_body': '"Tracking a Category means that the Dashboard will count edits to any articles in that Category. By default (depth 0), only the articles that are directly in that Category will be tracked. You can increase the depth value (up to a maximum of 3) if you want to include articles that are in sub-categories of that Category. Be sure to browse the Category first, to make sure the sub-Categories match what you intend to track."', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 14, 21, 7, 30, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ragesoss', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1230174675, 'comment_body': '"You can track articles based on a Template that they contain, which works whether the Template is used on article itself, or on the corresponding Talk page — such as WikiProject templates."', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 14, 21, 11, 18, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ragesoss', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1230175838, 'comment_body': '"Templates are used for a wide variety of purposes on wiki pages, but some are specific to a topic. Navigation templates, WikiProject templates, and topic-specific Infobox templates are particularly useful when using a Template to configure an Article Scoped Program."', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 14, 21, 12, 51, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ragesoss', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1230177725, 'comment_body': '"PetScan is a tool that allows you to query wiki pages based on a wide range of criteria — including categories, templates, wikilinks, and much more. You can use a PetScan query ID to configure a set of articles to track on the Dashboard."', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 14, 21, 15, 11, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ragesoss', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1230180545, 'comment_body': '"PagePile is a tool on Wikimedia Cloud.  It allows users to collect and organize a group of wiki pages into a single bundle called a "pile." These piles can then be easily shared with others, enabling collaborative work and information sharing.
 
In contrast to PetScan, the articles in a pile will not change over time, even when categories, templates or other data used to create that set of articles have changed."', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 14, 21, 18, 41, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ragesoss', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1230187253, 'comment_body': '"PetScan is a powerful but complex tool for querying a set of wiki pages based on a wide variety of criteria and data sources. You can use PetScan directly to create the query for a set of articles you want to track, which gives you access to the full set of options to target your query very precisely. Alternatively, you can create a PetScan query from some of the most common options directly from the Dashboard.

PetScan saves the query parameters and provides an ID for that query. The results of that query may change over time, for example when new articles are added to category that the query includes. The Dashboard will periodically refresh the query results for a given ID, and will update its statistics based on the latest set of articles that PetScan produces."

          ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 14, 21, 26, 27, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ragesoss', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1230188661, 'comment_body': 'What is this used for?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 14, 21, 27, 35, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ragesoss', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1230684263, 'comment_body': '![image](https://github.com/WikiEducationFoundation/WikiEduDashboard/assets/10794178/663529b2-2c90-403a-b585-8b1650e01b76)

I can enter the same values as a Category and a Template separately (not via PetScan) and those categories show a non-zero article count. The Category actually only includes pages in the Wikipedia namespace, while the template is a talk page template. But I would at least have expected the PetScan query to return results based on the template.

I note that the PetScan UI shows 'Intersection' rather than 'Union' for the category part, when I view that query. And I note that only mainspace (the unlabeled one) is selected on the 'Page properties' tab, which is possibly why the template didn't return any results.

pr_title: improve styling for articles that don't exist
pr_review_comments: [{'comment_id': 1231136753, 'comment_body': "Why do you prefer this over adding a CSS class when the article doesn't exist?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 15, 14, 50, 17, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ragesoss', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1231140530, 'comment_body': "just a personal preference - having local styles means that it won't affect any other thing on the page. CSS classes end up conflicting and there's a lot more to think of just to be sure they aren't affecting anything else. \n\nOf course doesn't matter here so I could switch to using a class. Your call. pr_title: prevent subcategories from showing up in article titles
pr_body: This was caused by the fact that we were always passing `namespace` to `category_query` - even when it was `nil`. This meant that the default `0` value for namespace was always ignored.
